(1) The Secretary of State may by regulations provide that—
(a) persons of a prescribed description do not qualify for the national minimum wage; or
(b) prescribed provisions of this Act apply in relation to persons of a prescribed description with prescribed modifications.

(2) The power conferred by subsection (1) above includes power to make provision by reference to factors such as—
(a) a person's age;
(b) a person's occupation;
(c) the capacity in which a person works;
(d) the person by or for whom a person works;
(e) the type of work done.

(1) An officer acting for the purposes of this Act shall have power for the performance of his duties—
(a) to require the production of, and inspect and examine, any records relevant to ascertaining whether or not the national minimum wage has been or is being paid to a worker;
(b) to require any person keeping such records to give to the officer any information and explanation that the officer considers necessary;
(c) at all reasonable times to enter any relevant premises in order to exercise any power conferred on him by paragraph (a) or (b) above.

(3) If an officer acting for the purposes of this Act is of the opinion that a worker who qualifies for the national minimum wage has not been remunerated for any pay reference period by his employer at a rate at least equal to the national minimum wage, the officer may serve a notice ("a notice of underpayment") on the employer.

(1) Section 104A of the Employment Rights Act 1996 (unfair dismissal: national minimum wage) provides that an employee who is dismissed shall be regarded for the purposes of Part X of that Act as unfairly dismissed if the reason (or, if more than one, the principal reason) for the dismissal is that—
(a) any action was taken, or was proposed to be taken, by or on behalf of the employee with a view to enforcing, or otherwise securing the benefit of, a right of the employee's to which this section applies;
(b) the employer was prosecuted for an offence under section 31 as a result of action taken by or on behalf of the employee;
(c) the employee qualifies, or will or might qualify, for the national minimum wage or for a particular rate of national minimum wage.
